{
  "moduleId": "smolen",
  "displayName": "Smolen",
  "category": "notrump-responses",
  "defaultRole": "responder",
  "fixtureVersion": 1,
  "description": "Jump to 3H/3S after Stayman denial to show 5-4 in majors, game-forcing",
  "purpose": "Handle the 5-4 major hand with game values after Stayman gets a 2D denial — let opener choose the fit while keeping the strong hand as declarer",
  "scopeNote": "Responder shows 5-4 majors, game-forcing, after `1NT-2C-2D` (and mirrored after 2NT and strong-NT overcalls) by jumping in the 4-card major to right-side the contract. The BridgeBum-backed 'slow' 3M acceptance branch and the responder 4M follow-ups are retained as discovery-pinned extensions, not authority mechanics. Whether 2NT / natural-NT-overcall applicability belongs in this module vs a separate module is deferred.",
  "references": {
    "authority": {
      "url": "https://www.larryco.com/bridge-articles/smolen",
      "label": "Larry Cohen — Smolen: bid the shorter major at the 3-level after 1NT–2C–2D to right-side game",
      "snapshot": {
        "text": "# Smolen Convention Article\n\n**By: Larry Cohen**\n\nSmolen is a convention used by a responder to a notrump opening bid (or natural notrump overcall). It applies when the responder holds 5-4 in the majors (either distribution) with enough strength for game.\n\n## Example Hand\n\nAfter partner opens 1NT with:\n- Spades: AJ542\n- Hearts: KJ87\n- Diamonds: 2\n- Clubs: J103\n\nBegin with Stayman. If opener shows a 4-card major, the hand is straightforward. However, if opener responds 2♦ (denying a major), the situation becomes more complex.\n\nWhile 4♥ is no longer possible (no 4-4 fit), 4♠ remains viable (a 5-3 fit could exist). The responder must indicate possession of 5 spades and must force to game.\n\nIn Standard bidding, responder jumps to 3♠, announcing 5 spades and game-forcing values. By inference, this shows 4 hearts (otherwise, a plain transfer to spades would have been used instead of Stayman). The sequence 1NT–2♣–2♦–3-of-Major shows 5 in that major, 4 in the other major, and game strength. Opener then chooses between 3NT or responder's 5-card major.\n\n## The Smolen Advantage\n\nThe Smolen convention improves on this auction. Instead of jumping from 2♦ into his five-card major, responder jumps into his four-card major. This approach ensures the strong hand plays the contract when the five-card major is chosen—advantageous for opening lead purposes.\n\nUsing Smolen, the sequence 1NT–2♣–2♦–3-of-a-Major shows 5 cards in the other major and, by inference, four cards in the major bid.\n\n## Smolen After 2NT\n\nSmolen also applies after 2NT–3♣–3♦. Responder bids the major where he holds 4 cards, thereby showing 5 in the other major and potentially \"right-siding\" the contract.\n\nAdditionally, Smolen applies after a natural strong notrump overcall (systems on).\n",
        "fetchedAt": "2026-04-19"
      }
    },
    "discovery": {
      "url": "https://www.bridgebum.com/smolen.php"
    }
  },
  "teaching": {
    "tradeoff": "Smolen uses jump bids (3H/3S) that could otherwise be used as natural invitational bids.",
    "principle": "Bid the shorter major at the 3-level — this tells opener about both majors and lets the strong hand declare.",
    "commonMistakes": [
      {
        "text": "Do not forget that the jump shows the short major.",
        "reason": "Bidding the long major misdescribes the hand and wrong-sides the contract."
      },
      {
        "text": "Do not use Smolen without game values.",
        "reason": "The jump forces the auction to game and removes invitational room."
      },
      {
        "text": "Do not bypass simpler methods with only one major.",
        "reason": "Transfers or ordinary Stayman describe single-suited hands more accurately."
      },
      {
        "text": "Do not assume opener's three-level acceptance is part of the primary Cohen treatment.",
        "reason": "Cohen describes opener choosing 3NT or game in responder's major; the slower three-level acceptance branch is a partnership extension covered by the discovery reference."
      }
    ]
  },
